            <section class="mt-10 prose">
              <h2>How this chain drive design calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool implements a simplified roller chain drive design
                procedure inspired by common industrial guides (Renold, SKF,
                iwis, etc.). It is intended for preliminary sizing and
                educational use, not as a substitute for a full
                manufacturer-specific design.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Design power</h3>
              <p>
                First, the transmitted power is adjusted by a service factor to
                account for load fluctuations, start/stop frequency and daily
                operating hours:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Design power</strong></p>
                <p>\( P_d = P \cdot K_s \)</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( P_d \) = design power</li>
                  <li>\( P \) = nominal power from the motor</li>
                  <li>\( K_s \) = service factor (typically 1.0–1.8)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Chain size selection</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator compares the design power with a small internal
                table of typical allowable powers for standard chain sizes at
                1500&nbsp;rpm. The table is intentionally conservative and only
                covers a few common sizes (e.g. 08B, 10B, 12B or ANSI #40, #50,
                #60).
              </p>
              <p>
                The smallest chain whose allowable power is greater than the
                design power is selected. If the design power exceeds the
                largest size in the table, the tool will warn you that a larger
                or multiple-strand chain is required.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Sprocket tooth counts and speed ratio</h3>
              <p>The speed ratio is defined as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( i = \dfrac{N_2}{N_1} = \dfrac{z_2}{z_1} \)</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( N_1 \) = driver speed (rpm)</li>
                  <li>\( N_2 \) = driven speed (rpm)</li>
                  <li>\( z_1 \) = driver sprocket teeth</li>
                  <li>\( z_2 \) = driven sprocket teeth</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                If you do not specify tooth counts, the calculator chooses a
                reasonable driver tooth count (typically between 17 and 25) and
                computes the driven tooth count from the ratio, rounding to the
                nearest integer.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Chain length and center distance</h3>
              <p>
                For a given pitch \( p \), tooth counts \( z_1, z_2 \) and
                center distance \( a \), the approximate number of chain pitches
                (links) is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( L_p = \dfrac{2a}{p} + \dfrac{z_1 + z_2}{2} + \dfrac{(z_2 -
                  z_1)^2}{4\pi^2} \cdot \dfrac{p}{a} \)
                </p>
                <p>\( L = \text{nearest even integer to } L_p \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Chains must have an even number of pitches, so the calculator
                rounds to the nearest even integer and then recomputes the exact
                center distance corresponding to that integer number of links.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Chain speed</h3>
              <p>
                Chain speed is checked against typical recommended limits (often
                3–15&nbsp;m/s for standard roller chains):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( v = \dfrac{\pi \, d_1 \, N_1}{60} \)</p>
                <p>
                  with \( d_1 \) the pitch circle diameter of the driver
                  sprocket.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The pitch circle diameter is approximated from pitch and tooth
                count:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( d = \dfrac{p}{\sin(\pi / z)} \)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>Interpreting the safety factor</h3>
              <p>
                The “safety factor (power)” reported by the calculator is the
                ratio between the catalogue allowable power for the selected
                chain size and your design power:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( SF = \dfrac{P_\text{allow}}{P_d} \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Values above 1.0 indicate that the chain is theoretically
                adequate for power transmission. For industrial drives,
                designers often target safety factors of 1.2–1.5 or higher
                depending on the application and manufacturer recommendations.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical chain drive design tips</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Keep the driver sprocket tooth count ≥ 17 to reduce polygonal
                  action and vibration.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Avoid extremely small or extremely large speed ratios in a
                  single chain stage.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Keep the chain speed within the limits recommended by the
                  chain manufacturer.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Provide for tension adjustment (idler or movable center
                  distance) to compensate for wear and elongation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Always cross-check final selections with the manufacturer’s
                  detailed design guide and catalogue data.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Disclaimer</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator uses simplified formulas and a reduced internal
                chain table for convenience. Real-world chain drive design must
                consider many additional factors (environment, lubrication,
                strand count, fatigue, shock loads, standards compliance, etc.).
                Always validate the results with the official documentation of
                your chosen chain supplier and applicable engineering standards.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-10">
