              <div class="space-y-3 text-sm" id="faq-container">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What inputs do I need to design a chain drive?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
                    At minimum you need the transmitted power, driving shaft
                    speed, desired speed ratio (or driven speed), approximate
                    center distance and an idea of the service conditions
                    (shock, duty cycle). With these, the calculator can propose
                    a chain size, sprocket tooth counts and chain length.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How accurate is the selected chain size?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
                    The size is based on a small generic table of allowable
                    powers and is suitable for preliminary design. For critical
                    or high‑power applications you should always confirm the
                    selection using the specific catalogue and design guide of
                    the chain manufacturer you plan to use.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Why must the chain have an even number of links?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
                    Standard roller chains are assembled from alternating inner
                    and outer links. This construction requires an even number
                    of pitches. The calculator automatically rounds the
                    theoretical link count to the nearest even integer and
                    adjusts the center distance accordingly.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What if my design power is higher than the largest chain
